final_answer("Yes, Windows has similar capabilities via PowerShell. To list installed software (MSI), you can use: `Get-WmiObject -Query 'Select * From Win32_Product' | Select-Object -Property Name`. For Windows Store apps, use: `Get-AppxPackage -AllUsers`.

To implement this in Rust, you can use `std::process::Command` to call powershell.exe:

```rust
use std::process::Command;
use std::str;

fn main() {
    let mut command = Command::new("powershell.exe");
    command.arg("-Command");
    command.arg("Get-WmiObject -Query \"Select * From Win32_Product\" | Select-Object -Property Name");
    let output = command.output().expect("Failed to execute command");

    let output_str = str::from_utf8(&output.stdout).unwrap();
    println!("{}", output_str);
}
```
Note: `Win32_Product` only tracks software installed via Windows Installer. For a more comprehensive list, you might need to query the Registry or use `Get-AppxPackage` for modern apps.")
